  "doc_id": "44906",
  "text": "Lagrangian markers located at the object surface immersed in a fluid. The fluid and solid phases share the physical properties at the \"immersed\" boundary by mutual interpolation between the Eulerian and Lagrangian references via a pseudo delta function as a weight function. The method has demonstrated its versatileness through applications to a number of problems including blood flow in a heart [CITATION_1] , and deformable biological cells experiencing shear [CITATION_2] and motion of aquatic animals [CITATION_3] . The IB method has also inspired many researchers to propose a number of improved methods. For example, to facilitate the application to medical problems, Zhang and co-workers [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] proposed (in their immersed finite element method) a new kernel function, instead of the pseudo delta function, for determining the cut-off region around the interface on a non-uniform mesh system. Also, the immersed interface treatment [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] improves the sharpness of the interface by incorporating the jump in the stress and velocities across the interface.",
